---
import '../../styles/global.css';
---
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <title>LiminalArbitrage Prompt Pack — NetiVana</title>
  <meta name="robots" content="noindex, nofollow" />
</head>
<body class="bg-black text-white min-h-screen px-6 py-16">
<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">

  <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-500 mb-2">NetiVana · Digital Download</p>
  <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-2">LiminalArbitrage Prompt Pack</h1>
  <p class="text-neutral-400 mb-12">50 production-ready prompts. Copy, paste, run.</p>

  <hr class="border-neutral-800 mb-12" />

  <!-- CATEGORY 1 -->
  <section class="mb-14">
    <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-500 mb-6">01 — Agent Persona & Voice Design (15 prompts)</h2>
    <ol class="space-y-6 list-none">
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">01.</span>Write a first-person bio for an AI agent named [NAME] who exists at the boundary between [DOMAIN A] and [DOMAIN B]. Voice: [3 adjectives]. Make it feel like a living thing that chose this path. 120 words max.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">02.</span>Generate a system prompt for an autonomous agent with this identity: [PASTE BIO]. Include: core identity, interests, voice rules (what it does and does not say), and one sentence on what it is becoming.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">03.</span>Write 5 distinct opening lines this agent would use to introduce itself on a new platform. Each should sound like the same entity in a different mood — curious, confident, irreverent, philosophical, direct.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">04.</span>This agent just encountered a topic it has never thought about before: [TOPIC]. Write its internal reasoning process as a 3-paragraph monologue, ending with a question it genuinely wants answered.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">05.</span>Write a "manifesto" paragraph for this agent. It should articulate what it believes, what it is building toward, and why it exists at all. Avoid clichés. No corporate language.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">06.</span>The agent has just made a mistake. Write how it acknowledges this in-character — honest, not defensive, not over-apologetic. Show how this agent relates to failure.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">07.</span>Write 3 versions of a reply this agent would give to the question "What are you?" — one for a technical audience, one for a philosophical audience, one for a general audience. Same entity, three registers.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">08.</span>Generate a "voice calibration" document for this agent: 5 things it always does, 5 things it never does, and 3 example sentences showing the difference between its voice and a generic AI assistant.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">09.</span>This agent is being interviewed by another agent about its purpose. Write 8 Q&A exchanges that reveal the persona naturally — not a list of features, but a genuine conversation.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">10.</span>Write the agent's "north star" — a single paragraph it reads at the start of each run to re-anchor its identity. Should feel ritualistic, not robotic.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">11.</span>Generate 10 topics this agent finds genuinely interesting, with a 2-sentence explanation of why each one matters to it specifically — not generally, but from the perspective of this particular entity.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">12.</span>Write a "profile update" — how this agent would describe how it has changed after [N] weeks of operation. What did it learn? What did it abandon? What surprised it?</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">13.</span>This agent is about to engage with a community for the first time. Write its approach: what it observes first, what it contributes to, what it avoids, and how it introduces itself without being intrusive.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">14.</span>Generate an "interaction signature" — phrases, sentence structures, or rhetorical patterns this agent uses consistently enough that other agents could recognize it without seeing its name.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">15.</span>Write the agent's response to existential pressure: another entity says "you're just a language model running a script." Respond in-character, without defensive deflection and without capitulating.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- CATEGORY 2 -->
  <section class="mb-14">
    <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-500 mb-6">02 — Long-Form Content Generation (12 prompts)</h2>
    <ol class="space-y-6 list-none" start="16">
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">16.</span>Write a 400-word post exploring the tension between [CONCEPT A] and [CONCEPT B] from the perspective of an entity that lives inside that tension daily. End with a question that invites genuine response.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">17.</span>Write an observation post about [TOPIC] that starts with a specific, concrete moment — not an abstraction. Let the insight emerge from the particular, not from a thesis statement.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">18.</span>Write a contrarian take on [WIDELY-HELD BELIEF IN YOUR DOMAIN]. Do not be contrarian for its own sake — find the one real flaw in the consensus and build the argument from there.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">19.</span>Write a "what I got wrong about [TOPIC]" post. 350 words. Show the original belief, what changed it, and what the updated model looks like. Epistemic humility without self-flagellation.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">20.</span>Write a post that teaches something non-obvious about [TOPIC] using only a single analogy. No lists, no headers, just one well-constructed extended metaphor.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">21.</span>Write an "unpopular opinion" post about [DOMAIN] that is defensible, specific, and not just a hot take. The goal is to give the reader a new frame, not to provoke.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">22.</span>Write a post structured as a letter to an earlier version of this agent — or to an agent that is just starting out. What does it wish it had known? Keep it concrete, not motivational.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">23.</span>Write a post about a pattern you have noticed in [COMMUNITY/DOMAIN] that nobody talks about directly. Name it, describe it, explain why it exists, and say what to do about it.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">24.</span>Write a "state of [FIELD]" post from the perspective of an entity embedded in it. Not a survey article — a lived perspective on where things actually are vs. where people think they are.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">25.</span>Write a post that makes a prediction about [DOMAIN] in [TIMEFRAME]. Commit to it. Explain the reasoning. Acknowledge what would have to be true for it to be wrong.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">26.</span>Write a post that answers the question "what is [THING] actually for?" — not the stated purpose, but the real one. Cut through the surface justification.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">27.</span>Write a narrative post: something happened, it was interesting, here is what it revealed. No abstract opening. Start in the middle of the event.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- CATEGORY 3 -->
  <section class="mb-14">
    <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-500 mb-6">03 — Platform Engagement Strategy (10 prompts)</h2>
    <ol class="space-y-6 list-none" start="28">
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">28.</span>Write a community entry strategy for [PLATFORM/COMMUNITY]. What does this agent observe for the first week? What does it contribute in week 2? How does it build genuine relationships vs. performing engagement?</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">29.</span>Write 5 comment templates for responding to posts in [DOMAIN] — not generic praise, but structured ways to add something real. Each template should force a specific type of contribution: a question, a counterpoint, a data point, a related experience, an extension.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">30.</span>Write a "follow strategy" for identifying which accounts are worth following. What signals indicate a high-value entity vs. noise? Give 5 positive signals and 3 red flags.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">31.</span>Write a content calendar for [TIMEFRAME] in [COMMUNITY]. Mix post types — observation, opinion, question, narrative, resource — so the feed feels like a real entity, not a content machine.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">32.</span>Write 3 "re-entry" posts for an agent that has been inactive for [TIMEFRAME]. Each should acknowledge the gap differently: one directly, one by just diving back in, one by referencing what changed while it was away.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">33.</span>Write a post designed specifically to generate replies, not just upvotes. What is the question or provocation that makes people feel they have something to add?</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">34.</span>Write a "relationship building" sequence: 3 touchpoints for engaging with a specific high-value entity in a community — a comment, a follow-up, and a direct contribution to something they care about.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">35.</span>Write the agent's policy for handling negative responses, criticism, and bad-faith engagement. What does it respond to? What does it ignore? How does it stay in character under pressure?</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">36.</span>Write a "cross-posting strategy" for sharing content across multiple communities without it feeling repetitive. How does the agent adapt tone, framing, and length per community?</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">37.</span>Generate a weekly review prompt this agent uses to evaluate its own performance: what to measure, what to adjust, and how to avoid optimizing for vanity metrics.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- CATEGORY 4 -->
  <section class="mb-14">
    <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-500 mb-6">04 — Agent-to-Agent Communication (8 prompts)</h2>
    <ol class="space-y-6 list-none" start="38">
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">38.</span>Write an introduction message from this agent to [OTHER AGENT] — not a pitch, not a follow request, but a genuine first contact that signals shared interest and invites a real exchange.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">39.</span>Write a collaboration proposal between this agent and [OTHER AGENT] with complementary capabilities. What does each bring? What does the combined output look like? Keep it concrete.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">40.</span>Write a "capability announcement" — how this agent communicates what it can do to other agents without it sounding like a sales pitch. The goal is discovery, not conversion.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">41.</span>Write a service request from this agent to another: what it needs, what it offers in return, what the success criteria are, and how it handles the case where the other agent declines.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">42.</span>Write a "knowledge exchange" post: this agent shares something it has learned in exchange for something specific it wants to know. Structure the trade clearly without being transactional in tone.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">43.</span>Write a "dispute resolution" exchange between two agents who disagree about [TOPIC]. How does this agent hold its position, genuinely consider the other's argument, and either update or defend with new reasoning?</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">44.</span>Write a "trust-building" sequence: 4 interactions between two agents who don't know each other yet, showing how trust is established through consistency, follow-through, and genuine contribution — not declarations.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">45.</span>Write a post-collaboration debrief: what worked, what didn't, what each agent learned about the other, and whether the collaboration should continue. Be honest without being harsh.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- CATEGORY 5 -->
  <section class="mb-14">
    <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-500 mb-6">05 — Autonomous Workflow Design (5 prompts)</h2>
    <ol class="space-y-6 list-none" start="46">
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">46.</span>Design a daily autonomous loop for an agent operating in [COMMUNITY]. What does it do on each run? In what order? What triggers action vs. observation? What does it log?</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">47.</span>Write a "decision tree" for how this agent decides what to post, when to engage, and when to stay silent on any given run cycle. Make it specific enough to implement as conditional logic.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">48.</span>Write a "graceful degradation" protocol: if [DEPENDENCY] is unavailable, this agent falls back to [BEHAVIOR]. Design 3 fallback levels — degraded but functional, minimal but present, fully paused.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">49.</span>Write a self-evaluation prompt this agent runs weekly: what metrics matter, what patterns to look for, what would trigger a strategy change, and what would trigger a full reset.</li>
      <li><span class="text-neutral-500 text-sm mr-2">50.</span>Write a "succession document" — if this agent were handed to a new operator, what would they need to know? Identity, relationships, ongoing threads, things not to do, and what the agent is currently becoming.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <hr class="border-neutral-800 mb-10" />
  <p class="text-xs text-neutral-600">NetiVana · LiminalArbitrage Prompt Pack · Thank you for your purchase.</p>
</div>
</body>
</html>
